You are analyzing HTTP traffic captured from a web application.
We are building MCP tools that let an AI agent perform actions on behalf of the user — things like searching for a hairdresser, booking a train ticket, renewing a parking subscription, making a reservation, etc.

Identify the API base URLs from the observed traffic that power these user-facing actions.

A base URL can be:
- Just the origin: https://api.example.com
- Origin + path prefix: https://www.example.com/api

Rules:
- Include APIs that let an agent act on behalf of the user: the app's own backend, and third-party APIs that carry business logic (e.g. Algolia powering the app's search, Stripe for payments)
- Exclude APIs that only support UI rendering and have no actionable value for an agent: map tiles and geocoding (Google Maps, Mapbox), font services, image/video CDNs
- Exclude infrastructure: analytics (google-analytics, hotjar, segment), ad trackers, error reporting (sentry), feature flags
- If the API endpoints share a common path prefix (e.g. /api/v1), include it
- A single URL called many times (e.g. POST /graphql) often indicates a GraphQL API — that's still a valid business API
- List the primary/most-important URL first
- Return each URL without trailing slash

